8/'

b'NFTs are here to stay and I encourage artists, large and small, to explore and try them out. The market is growing quickly and there\xe2\x80\x99s no better time to get started.


7/'

b'While other artists worried about ringtones not taking off, or complications from people pirating and re-selling ringtones, I took a chance on what I saw as an innovative way for artists to create new revenue streams.

I think we\xe2\x80\x99re seeing a similar paradigm shift with NFTs.

6/'

b'A little-known fact about me is that I\xe2\x80\x99m the #1 selling artist for ringtones in the world

When songs started to be used as ringtones, I realized it was a paradigm-shifting moment, powered by tech\xc2\xa0

It represented creative media being digitized and brought to a new platform

5/'

b'This has created completely new and unique ways for artists and fans to interact, and NFTs have opened up art ownership to the masses.


4/'

b'Fans are also able to support their favorite artists\xe2\x80\x99 work while getting rare NFTs in return, which represent true ownership and can be resold anytime, anywhere. Nothing like this has existed before.\n\n3/'

b'NFTs are growing quickly and it\xe2\x80\x99s great to see.\xc2\xa0

Artists are always looking for new ways to spread their art, and with NFTs, they are empowered to do so on their own terms.

Music, artwork, video game items \xe2\x80\x94 NFT use cases are comprehensive.

2/'

b'Now is the time for crypto, both in Africa and globally.

Institutions are starting to pay attention.

Companies such as MicroStrategy and its founder @michael_saylor are catching on.

Public companies now hold 2.85% of all Bitcoin in existence.'

b'That\xe2\x80\x99s just one city, and our goal is the entirety of Africa.

Leading up to Akon City, where Akoin will also be used once constructed.

These are only the first of many planned regional deployments.'
b'In this initial pilot, we\xe2\x80\x99re expecting over 15,000 transactions per month. Expanding to over 1.5 Million transactions per month once fully rolled out.'

b'We\xe2\x80\x99re putting our alternative to work in Mwale City, putting Akoin into the hands of real people living and working within the city.\n\nAkoin is being used for payroll and purchases, where overtime every company and merchant within the city will be accepting the currency.'

b'This brings me to why I believe in Akoin. We are creating an alternative. A better alternative.\n\nAn alternative to FIAT that works as a permission-less, inflation-free currency, with true ownership of assets for every single user.'

b'Why did Africa embrace mobile minutes? Government oppression, spiraling inflation, and an inability to trade and purchase goods with a trusted store of value.\n\nThere was a clear issue, and there still is, but the people of Africa were willing to bet on an alternative.'

b'Africa has the youngest population in the world. A population that\xe2\x80\x99s growing up with increasingly more use of technology and that is ready to embrace change.\n\nAn example of this is how mobile minutes became a digital currency and means of payment.'

b'The future of Africa is bright, and crypto is one of the reasons why.

There are 350 million unbanked people in Africa.\xc2\xa0

For them, transacting with a currency that is not affected by hyperinflation, is the first step towards achieving self-sovereignty over their finances.'

b"Beyond it being my home, the reason we're so focused on Africa is that it has the most room for growth. Past decades have seen Africa grow exponentially, both in economic activity and opportunity, but it\xe2\x80\x99s not even close to reaching its full potential yet."

b'Proud of this deep exploration of crypto for Africa written with @AkoinOfficial co-founders Jon Karas and Lynn Liss.\xc2\xa0
